“You will be challenged during the next four years, but you can do it,” said Academy Superintendent Lt. Gen. Richard Clark. “Take one bite at a time. The first step is completing basic cadet training, and you have already demonstrated you have what it takes to succeed by getting here. I stood where you stand almost 40 years ago and I’m so glad I stuck it out.”

The global COVID-19 pandemic may be on the decline, but the Air Force Academy took no chances when more than 1,100 young men and women reported to the school for basic cadet training, June 24.

The trainees arrived between 7 a.m.-noon, were given facemasks, and immediately tested for the coronavirus.

Check out more on this story at www.usafa.edu.

node.text: Today, cadets march in a Founders Day Parade honoring the legacy of #youracademy. Together, we stand on the foundation built by those who came before us, striving to strengthen that foundation for those who come after us, reinforcing our bonds with a culture of dignity and respect. Being part of the Long Blue Line means being part of something bigger than ourselves, collectively building and bolstering the bridge to the future @usairforce  and  @spaceforcedod. The more we treat each other with dignity and respect, and ensure that this is a fundamental part of our culture, the higher we’ll rise together.

node.text:
As we honor Black History Month, I’d like to take a moment to share with you one of my favorite stories about Rosa Parks. I share this in hopes that when we think of civil rights exemplars such as Rosa Parks, the Tuskegee Airmen, Dr. Martin Luther King, and the many other pioneers of integration and racial equality, that we also reflect on ourselves. How can we better ourselves and understand that together we have an opportunity to become not only better Air and Space Forces, but a nation that champions diversity and inclusion?

#blackhistorymonth #leadership #diversityandinclusion

Six Air Force hockey players were named to the Krampade All-American Scholars team, as announced by the American Hockey Coaches Association (AHCA).

Due to the effects of Covid-19, the AHCA adopted revised criteria for this year's honorees. To qualify, a student-athlete must have attained a 3.6 GPA for each semester, regardless of whether the school's hockey team was able to play this season or not. Normally, a student-athlete is required to participate in a minimum of 40% of a team's games.

The six Falcons named to the team are: graduated senior Erik Anderson (3.87/3.73 – management), rising sophomore Sam Brennan (3.87/ 4.00 – undeclared), graduated senior Shawn Knowlton (3.66/3.93 – management), rising junior Brandon Koch (3.72/3.76 – operations research), rising sophomore Luke Robinson (3.97/3.97 – operations research) and rising junior Dalton Weigel (3.88/3.64 – legal studies).

node.text:
C1C Erika Willis ('22) completed a biomedical research summer internship at the Oklahoma Medical Research Foundation. She studied under the guidance of Courtney Griffin, Ph.D., working to observe the expression of proteins in the lungs to better understand the lungs’ susceptibility to inflammatory infections.

“Everything about this experience was great,” said Willis, a biology major at #YourAcademy. “It’s not just that it’s an incredible learning experience, but also that everyone here is so willing to help. I’ve dreamed of being a doctor since elementary school, and this one-of-a-kind experience has shown me the foundation of medicine and what I want to do with my life.”

Willis completed the John H. Saxon Service Academy Summer Research Program alongside two midshipmen from the @usnavalacademy in Annapolis, Maryland.
